# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: structured-data-schema
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:structured-data-schema/global-attributes-itemtype] The global attribute **`itemtype`** specifies the URL of the vocabulary that will be used to define `itemprop`'s (item properties) in the data structure.
[src:structured-data-schema/global-attributes-itemtype] `itemscope` is used to set the scope of where in the data structure the vocabulary set by `itemtype` will be active.
[src:structured-data-schema/global-attributes-itemtype] Google and other major search engines support the schema.org vocabulary for structured data.
[src:structured-data-schema/global-attributes-itemtype] This vocabulary defines a standard set of type names and property names.
[src:structured-data-schema/global-attributes-itemtype] For example, `MusicEvent` indicates a concert performance, with `startDate` and `location` properties specifying the concert's key details.
[src:structured-data-schema/global-attributes-itemtype] In this case, `MusicEvent` would be the URL used by `itemtype`, with `startDate` and location as `itemprop`'s which `MusicEvent` defines.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Microdata is part of the WHATWG HTML Standard and is used to nest metadata within existing content on web pages.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Search engines and web crawlers can extract and process microdata from a web page and use it to provide a richer browsing experience for users.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Search engines benefit greatly from direct access to this structured data because it allows search engines to understand the information on web pages and provide more relevant results to users.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Microdata uses a supporting vocabulary to describe an item and name-value pairs to assign values to its properties.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Microdata is an attempt to provide a declarative way of annotating HTML elements with machine-readable tags than the similar approaches of using RDFa and classic microformats.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] At a high level, microdata consists of a group of name-value pairs.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] The groups are called items, and each name-value pair is a property.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Items and properties are represented by regular elements.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] This vocabulary defines a standard set of type names and property names, for example, Schema.org Music Event indicates a concert performance, with `startDate` and `location` properties to specify the concert's key details.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] In this case, Schema.org Music Event would be the URL used by `itemtype` and `startDate` and location would be `itemprop`'s that Schema.org Music Event defines.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Microdata vocabularies provide the semantics or meaning of an *`Item`*.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Web developers can design a custom vocabulary or use vocabularies available on the web, such as the widely used schema.org vocabulary.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] A collection of commonly used markup vocabularies are provided by Schema.org.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Major search engine operators like Google, Microsoft, and Yahoo! rely on the schema.org vocabulary to improve search results.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] For some purposes, an ad hoc vocabulary is adequate.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] For others, a vocabulary will need to be designed.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Where possible, authors are encouraged to re-use existing vocabularies, as this makes content re-use easier.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] In some cases, search engines covering specific regions may provide locally-specific extensions of microdata.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] For example, Yandex, a major search engine in Russia, supports microformats such as `hCard` (company contact information), `hRecipe` (food recipe), `hReview` (market reviews) and `hProduct` (product data) and provides its own format for the definition of the terms and encyclopedic articles.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] This extension was made to solve transliteration problems between the Cyrillic and Latin alphabets.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Due to the implementation of additional marking parameters of Schema's vocabulary, the indexation of information in Russian-language web-pages became considerably more successful.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] `itemid` – The unique, global identifier of an item.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] `itemprop` – Used to add properties to an item.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] Every HTML element may have an `itemprop` attribute specified, where an `itemprop` consists of a name and value pair.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] `itemref` – Properties that are not descendants of an element with the `itemscope` attribute can be associated with the item using an **itemref**.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] `itemref` provides a list of element ids (not `itemid`s) with additional properties elsewhere in the document.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] `itemscope` – The `itemscope` attribute (usually) works along with `itemtype` to specify that the HTML contained in a block is about a particular item.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] The `itemscope` attribute creates the *`Item`* and defines the scope of the itemtype associated with it.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] The `itemtype` attribute is a valid URL of a vocabulary (such as schema.org) that describes the item and its properties context.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] `itemtype` – Specifies the URL of the vocabulary that will be used to define `itemprop`'s (item properties) in the data structure.
[src:structured-data-schema/html-microdata] The `itemscope` attribute is used to set the scope of where in the data structure the vocabulary set by `itemtype` will be active.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] JSON-LD is based on the concept of a "context" that maps JSON object properties to concepts in an ontology using an RDF model.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] In order to map the JSON-LD syntax to RDF, JSON-LD allows values to be coerced to a specified type or tagged with a language.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] A context can be embedded directly in a JSON-LD document or put into a separate file and referenced from traditional JSON documents via an HTTP Link header.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] The example above describes a person, based on the FOAF (friend of a friend) ontology.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] First, the two JSON properties `name` and `homepage` and the type `Person` are mapped to concepts in the FOAF vocabulary and the value of the `homepage` property is specified to be of the type `@id`.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] In other words, the homepage id is specified to be an IRI in the context definition.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] Based on the RDF model, this allows the person described in the document to be unambiguously identified by an IRI.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] The use of resolvable IRIs allows RDF documents containing more information to be transcluded which enables clients to discover new data by following those links; this principle is known as 'Follow Your Nose'.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] By having all data semantically annotated as in the example, an RDF processor can identify that the document contains information about a person (`@type`) and if the processor understands the FOAF vocabulary it can determine which properties specify the person's name and homepage.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] The encoding is used by Schema.org, Google Knowledge Graph, and used mostly for search engine optimization activities.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] It has also been used for applications such as biomedical informatics, and representing provenance information.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] It is also the basis of Activity Streams, a format for "the exchange of information about potential and completed activities", and is used in ActivityPub, the federated social networking protocol.
[src:structured-data-schema/json-ld] Additionally, it is used in the context of Internet of Things (IoT), where a Thing Description, which is a JSON-LD document, describes the network facing interfaces of IoT devices.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] In 2013, because the W3C HTML Working Group failed to find someone to serve as an editor for the **Microdata HTML** specification, its development was terminated with a 'Note'.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] However, since that time, two new editors were selected, and five newer versions of the working draft have been published, the most recent being Working Draft 26 April 2018.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] Microdata vocabularies do not provide the semantics, or meaning of an Item.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] Web developers can design a custom vocabulary or use vocabularies available on the web.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] A collection of commonly used markup vocabularies are provided by Schema.org schemas which include: *Person*, "*Place*", *Event*, *Organization*, *Product*, *Review*, *Review-aggregate*, *Breadcrumb*, *Offer*, *Offer-aggregate*.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] The website schema.org was established by search engine operators like Google, Microsoft, Yahoo!, and Yandex, which use microdata markup to improve search results.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] For some purposes, an ad-hoc vocabulary is adequate.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] For example, Yandex, a major search engine in Russia, supports microformats such as hCard (company contact information), hRecipe (food recipe), hReview (market reviews) and hProduct (product data) and provides its own format for definition of the terms and encyclopedic articles.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] This extension was made in order to solve transliteration problems between the Cyrillic and Latin alphabets.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] After the implementation of additional parameters from Schema's vocabulary, indexation of information in Russian-language web-pages became more successful.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] As the above example shows, Microdata items can be nested.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] In this case, an item of type http://schema.org/PostalAddress is nested inside an item of type http://schema.org/Person.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] The following text shows how Google parses the Microdata from the above example code.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] Developers can test pages containing Microdata using Google's *Rich Snippet Testing Tool*.
[src:structured-data-schema/microdata-html] The same machine-readable terms can be used not only in HTML Microdata, but also in other annotations such as RDFa or JSON-LD in the markup, or in an external RDF file in a serialization such as RDF/XML, Notation3, or Turtle.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The RDFa community runs a wiki website to host tools, examples, and tutorials.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] RDFa was first proposed by Mark Birbeck in the form of a W3C note entitled *XHTML and RDF*, which was then presented to the Semantic Web Interest Group at the W3C's 2004 Technical Plenary.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Later that year the work became part of the sixth public Working Draft of XHTML 2.0.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Although it is generally assumed that RDFa was originally intended only for XHTML 2, in fact the purpose of RDFa was always to provide a way to add metadata to *any* XML-based language.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Indeed, one of the earliest documents bearing the *RDF/A Syntax* name has the sub-title *A collection of attributes for layering RDF on XML languages*.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The document was written by Mark Birbeck and Steven Pemberton, and was made available for discussion on October 11, 2004.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] In April 2007 the XHTML 2 Working Group produced a module to support RDF annotation within the XHTML 1 family.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] As an example, it included an extended version of XHTML 1.1 dubbed XHTML+RDFa 1.0.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Although described as not representing an intended direction in terms of a formal markup language from the W3C, limited use of the XHTML+RDFa 1.0 DTD did subsequently appear on the public Web.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] October 2007 saw the first public Working Draft of a document entitled *RDFa in XHTML: Syntax and Processing*.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] This superseded and expanded upon the April draft; it contained rules for creating an RDFa parser, as well as guidelines for organizations wishing to make practical use of the technology.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] In October 2008 RDFa 1.0 reached recommendation status.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] RDFa 1.1 reached recommendation status in June 2012.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] It differs from RDFa 1.0 in that it no longer relies on the XML-specific namespace mechanism.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Therefore, it is possible to use RDFa 1.1 with non-XML document types such as HTML 4 or HTML 5.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Details can be found in an appendix to HTML 5.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] An additional *RDFa 1.1 Primer* document was last updated 17 March 2015.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] There are some main well-defined variants of the basic concepts, that are used as reference and as abbreviation to the W3C standards.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] RDFa was defined in 2008 with the "RDFa in XHTML: Syntax and Processing" Recommendation.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Its first application was to be a module of XHTML.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The HTML applications remained, *"a collection of attributes and processing rules for extending XHTML to support RDF"* expanded to HTML5, are now expressed in a specialized standard, the "HTML+RDFa" (the last is *"HTML+RDFa 1.1 - Support for RDFa in HTML4 and HTML5"*).
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The *"HTML+RDFa"* syntax of 2008 was also termed *"RDFa 1.0"*, so, there is no "RDFa Core 1.0" standard.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] In general this 2008's *RDFa 1.0* is used with the old XHTML standards (as long as *RDFa 1.1* is used with XHTML5 and HTML5).
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Is the first generic (for HTML and XML) RDFa standard; the "RDFa Core 1.1" is in the Third Edition, since 2015.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] RDFa Lite consists of five attributes: vocab, typeof, property, resource, and prefix.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] RDFa 1.1 Lite is upwards compatible with RDFa 1.1.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] In 2009 the W3C was positioned to retain *RDFa Lite* as unique and definitive standard alternative to Microdata.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The position was confirmed with the publication of the HTML5 Recommendation in 2014.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The essence of RDFa is to provide a set of attributes that can be used to carry metadata in an XML language (hence the 'a' in RDFa).
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] optional attribute that specifies the RDF type(s) of the subject or the partner resource (the resource that the metadata is about).
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] There are five "principles of interoperable metadata" met by RDFa.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Additionally RDFa may benefit web accessibility as more information is available to assistive technology.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] There is a growing number of tools for better usage of RDFa vocabularies and RDFa annotation.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Simplified approaches to semantically annotate information items in webpages were greatly encouraged by the HTML+RDFa (released in 2008) and microformats (since ~2005) standards.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] As of 2013 these standards were encoding events, contact information, products, and so on.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The statistics of 2017 show that usage of HTML+RDFa is now less than that of Microformats.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] There are already a few RDFa editors available online.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] is an environment for semi-automatic (or automatic) annotation of documents for publishing on the Web using RDFa.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] It also includes an RDFa extraction tool to provide the user with a view of the annotated triples.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The following is an example of adding Dublin Core metadata to an XML element in an XHTML file.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The following is an example of a complete XHTML+RDFa 1.0 document.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] In the example above, the document URI can be seen as representing an HTML document, but the document URI plus the "#me" string `http://example.org/john-d/#me` represents the actual person, as distinct from a document about them.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The *foaf:primaryTopic* in the header tells us the URI of the person the document is about.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The *foaf:nick* property (in the first `span` element) contains a nickname for this person, and the *dc:creator* property (in the `meta` element) tells us who created the document.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The hyperlink to the Einstürzende Neubauten website contains `rel="foaf:interest"`, suggesting that John Doe is interested in this band.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The *foaf:interest* inside the second `p` element is referring to a book by ISBN.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The `resource` attribute defines a resource in a similar way to the `href` attribute, but without defining a hyperlink.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Further into the paragraph, a `span` element containing an `about` attribute defines the book as another resource to specify metadata about.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] The book title and author are defined within the contents of this tag using the *dc:title* and *dc:creator* properties.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] Note how the prefix foaf is still used without declaration.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] RDFa 1.1 automatically includes prefixes for popular vocabularies such as FOAF.
[src:structured-data-schema/rdfa] That is, it is recommended that all of these attributes are used: `vocab`, `typeof`, `property`; not only one of them.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] Much of the vocabulary on Schema.org was inspired by earlier formats, such as microformats, FOAF, and OpenCyc.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] Microformats, with its most dominant representative hCard, continue (as of 2015) to be published widely on the web, where the deployment of Schema.org has strongly increased between 2012 and 2014.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] In 2015, Google began supporting the JSON-LD format, and as of September, 2017 recommended using JSON-LD for structured data whenever possible.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] Despite the advantages of using Schema.org, adoption remained limited as of 2016.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] A survey in 2016 of 300 US-based marketing agencies and B2C advertisers across industries showing only 17% uptake.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] As of 2024 over 45 million web domains have used schema markup on their web pages.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] Validators, such as the deprecated Google Structured Data Testing Tool, or more recent Google Rich Results Test Tool, Schema.org Markup Validator, Yandex Microformat validator, and Bing Markup Validator can be used to test the validity of the data marked up with the schemas and Microdata.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] More recently, Google Search Console (formerly webmaster tools) has provided a report section for unparsable structured data.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] If any Schema code on a website is incorrect, it will show in this report.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] Some schema markups such as Organization and Person are commonly used to influence search results returned by Google's Knowledge Graph.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] The popularity of Schema.org has served for its use as a base for other schemas, such as the Croissant specification for machine-learning datasets.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] Schema vocabulary includes sets of types, each of which have related metadata properties that can be illustrated using predefined enumerations and Datatypes.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] Types are managed by schema.org and are regularly updated.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] As of June 2026, there are over 823 schema types.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] The following is an example of how to mark up information about a movie and its director using the Schema.org schemas and microdata.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] In order to mark up the data, the attribute `itemtype` along with the URL of the schema is used.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] The attribute `itemscope` defines the scope of the itemtype.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] The kind of the current item can be defined by using the attribute `itemprop`.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] In June 2026, the Google and Schema.org community announced schema.org usage statistics for the first time.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] It was published publicly in the official Schema.org GitHub repository in CSV and JSON formats.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] Schema.org invited other crawlers and indexers to contribute their own statistics to this initiative using the same open format.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] This dataset is updated monthly and shows Schema.org term usage across millions of domains.
[src:structured-data-schema/schema-org] To respect privacy, the counts are aggregated at the domain level and presented in popularity-range buckets.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A **data model** is an abstract model that organizes elements of data and standardizes how they relate to one another and to the properties of real-world entities.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] For instance, a data model may specify that the data element representing a car be composed of a number of other elements which, in turn, represent the color and size of the car and define its owner.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The corresponding professional activity is called generally *data modeling* or, more specifically, *database design*.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data models are typically specified by a data expert, data specialist, data scientist, data librarian, or a data scholar.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data modeling language and notation are often represented in graphical form as diagrams.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data model can sometimes be referred to as a data structure, especially in the context of programming languages.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data models are often complemented by function models, especially in the context of enterprise models.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data model explicitly determines the *structure of data*; conversely, **structured data** is data organized according to an explicit data model or data structure.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Structured data is in contrast to *unstructured data* and *semi-structured data*.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The term ***data model*** can refer to two distinct but closely related concepts.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Sometimes it refers to an abstract formalization of the objects and relationships found in a particular application domain: for example the customers, products, and orders found in a manufacturing organization.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] At other times it refers to the set of concepts used in defining such formalizations: for example concepts such as entities, attributes, relations, or tables.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] So the "data model" of a banking application may be defined using the entity–relationship "data model".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This article uses the term in both senses.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Managing large quantities of structured and unstructured data is a primary function of information systems.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data models describe the structure, manipulation, and integrity aspects of the data stored in data management systems such as relational databases.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] They may also describe data with a looser structure, such as word processing documents, email messages, pictures, digital audio, and video: XDM, for example, provides a data model for XML documents.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The main aim of data models is to support the development of information systems by providing the definition and format of data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] According to West and Fowler (1999) "if this is done consistently across systems then compatibility of data can be achieved.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] If the same data structures are used to store and access data then different applications can share data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The results of this are indicated above.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] However, systems and interfaces often cost more than they should, to build, operate, and maintain.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] They may also constrain the business rather than support it.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A major cause is that the quality of the data models implemented in systems and interfaces is poor".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The reason for these problems is a lack of standards that will ensure that data models will both meet business needs and be consistent.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data model explicitly determines the structure of data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Typical applications of data models include database models, design of information systems, and enabling exchange of data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Logical data model: describes the semantics, as represented by a particular data manipulation technology.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This consists of descriptions of tables and columns, object oriented classes, and XML tags, among other things.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Physical data model: describes the physical means by which data are stored.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This is concerned with partitions, CPUs, tablespaces, and the like.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The significance of this approach, according to ANSI, is that it allows the three perspectives to be relatively independent of each other.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Storage technology can change without affecting either the logical or the conceptual model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The table/column structure can change without (necessarily) affecting the conceptual model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In each case, of course, the structures must remain consistent with the other model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The table/column structure may be different from a direct translation of the entity classes and attributes, but it must ultimately carry out the objectives of the conceptual entity class structure.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Early phases of many software development projects emphasize the design of a conceptual data model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Such a design can be detailed into a logical data model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In later stages, this model may be translated into physical data model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] However, it is also possible to implement a conceptual model directly.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] One of the earliest pioneering works in modeling information systems was done by Young and Kent (1958), who argued for "a precise and abstract way of specifying the informational and time characteristics of a data processing problem".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] They wanted to create "a notation that should enable the analyst to organize the problem around any piece of hardware".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Their work was the first effort to create an abstract specification and invariant basis for designing different alternative implementations using different hardware components.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The next step in IS modeling was taken by CODASYL, an IT industry consortium formed in 1959, who essentially aimed at the same thing as Young and Kent: the development of "a proper structure for machine-independent problem definition language, at the system level of data processing".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This led to the development of a specific IS information algebra.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In the 1960s data modeling gained more significance with the initiation of the management information system (MIS) concept.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] According to Leondes (2002), "during that time, the information system provided the data and information for management purposes.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The first generation database system, called Integrated Data Store (IDS), was designed by Charles Bachman at General Electric.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Two famous database models, the network data model and the hierarchical data model, were proposed during this period of time".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Codd worked out his theories of data arrangement, and proposed the relational model for database management based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In the 1970s entity–relationship modeling emerged as a new type of conceptual data modeling, originally formalized in 1976 by Peter Chen.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Entity–relationship models were being used in the first stage of information system design during the requirements analysis to describe information needs or the type of information that is to be stored in a database.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This technique can describe any ontology, i.e., an overview and classification of concepts and their relationships, for a certain area of interest.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Nijssen developed "Natural Language Information Analysis Method" (NIAM) method, and developed this in the 1980s in cooperation with Terry Halpin into Object–Role Modeling (ORM).
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] However, it was Terry Halpin's 1989 PhD thesis that created the formal foundation on which Object–Role Modeling is based.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Bill Kent, in his 1978 book *Data and Reality,* compared a data model to a map of a territory, emphasizing that in the real world, "highways are not painted red, rivers don't have county lines running down the middle, and you can't see contour lines on a mountain".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In contrast to other researchers who tried to create models that were mathematically clean and elegant, Kent emphasized the essential messiness of the real world, and the task of the data modeler to create order out of chaos without excessively distorting the truth.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Harrington (2000), "the development of the object-oriented paradigm brought about a fundamental change in the way we look at data and the procedures that operate on data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Traditionally, data and procedures have been stored separately: the data and their relationship in a database, the procedures in an application program.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] During the early 1990s, three Dutch mathematicians Guido Bakema, Harm van der Lek, and JanPieter Zwart, continued the development on the work of G.M.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] They focused more on the communication part of the semantics.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In 1997 they formalized the method Fully Communication Oriented Information Modeling FCO-IM.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A database model is a specification describing how a database is structured and used.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Several such models have been suggested.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This may not strictly qualify as a data model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The flat (or table) model consists of a single, two-dimensional array of data elements, where all members of a given column are assumed to be similar values, and all members of a row are assumed to be related to one another.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The hierarchical model is similar to the network model except that links in the hierarchical model form a tree structure, while the network model allows arbitrary graph.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] , organizes data using two fundamental constructs, called records and sets.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Records (or nodes) contain fields (i.e. attributes), and sets (or edges) define one-to-many, many-to-many and many-to-one relationships between records: one owner, many members.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The network data model is an abstraction of the design concept used in the implementation of databases.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Network models emphasise interconnectedness, making them ideal for applications where relationships are crucial, like social networks or recommendation systems.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This structure allows for efficient querying of relationships without expensive joins.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] is a database model based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Its core idea is to describe a database as a collection of predicates over a finite set of predicate variables, describing constraints on the possible values and combinations of values.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The power of the relational data model lies in its mathematical foundations and a simple user-level paradigm.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A method of data modeling that has been defined as "attribute free", and "fact-based".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The result is a verifiably correct system, from which other common artifacts, such as ERD, UML, and semantic models may be derived.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Associations between data objects are described during the database design procedure, such that normalization is an inevitable result of the process.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The simplest style of data warehouse schema.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The star schema consists of a few "fact tables" (possibly only one, justifying the name) referencing any number of "dimension tables".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data structure diagram (DSD) is a diagram and data model used to describe conceptual data models by providing graphical notations which document entities and their relationships, and the constraints that bind them.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The basic graphic elements of DSDs are boxes, representing entities, and arrows, representing relationships.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data structure diagrams are most useful for documenting complex data entities.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data structure diagrams are an extension of the entity–relationship model (ER model).
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In DSDs, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as boxes composed of attributes which specify the constraints that bind entities together.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] DSDs differ from the ER model in that the ER model focuses on the relationships between different entities, whereas DSDs focus on the relationships of the elements within an entity and enable users to fully see the links and relationships between each entity.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with the notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The choices are between arrow heads, inverted arrow heads (crow's feet), or numerical representation of the cardinality.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] An entity–relationship model (ERM), sometimes referred to as an entity–relationship diagram (ERD), could be used to represent an abstract conceptual data model (or semantic data model or physical data model) used in software engineering to represent structured data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] There are several notations used for ERMs.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Like DSD's, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as lines, with the relationship constraints as descriptions on the line.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The E-R model, while robust, can become visually cumbersome when representing entities with several attributes.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with a notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data model in Geographic information systems is a mathematical construct for representing geographic objects or surfaces as data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Generic data models are generalizations of conventional data models.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] They define standardized general relation types, together with the kinds of things that may be related by such a relation type.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Generic data models are developed as an approach to solving some shortcomings of conventional data models.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] For example, different modelers usually produce different conventional data models of the same domain.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This can lead to difficulty in bringing the models of different people together and is an obstacle for data exchange and data integration.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Invariably, however, this difference is attributable to different levels of abstraction in the models and differences in the kinds of facts that can be instantiated (the semantic expression capabilities of the models).
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The modelers need to communicate and agree on certain elements that are to be rendered more concretely, in order to make the differences less significant.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A semantic data model in software engineering is a technique to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A semantic data model is an abstraction that defines how the stored symbols relate to the real world.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A semantic data model is sometimes called a conceptual data model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The logical data structure of a database management system (DBMS), whether hierarchical, network, or relational, cannot totally satisfy the requirements for a conceptual definition of data because it is limited in scope and biased toward the implementation strategy employed by the DBMS.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Therefore, the need to define data from a conceptual view has led to the development of semantic data modeling techniques.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] That is, techniques to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The real world, in terms of resources, ideas, events, etc., are symbolically defined within physical data stores.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Thus, the model must be a true representation of the real world.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data architecture is the design of data for use in defining the target state and the subsequent planning needed to hit the target state.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data architecture describes the data structures used by a business and/or its applications.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] There are descriptions of data in storage and data in motion; descriptions of data stores, data groups, and data items; and mappings of those data artifacts to data qualities, applications, locations, etc.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Essential to realizing the target state, Data architecture describes how data is processed, stored, and utilized in a given system.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It provides criteria for data processing operations that make it possible to design data flows and also control the flow of data in the system.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data modeling in software engineering is the process of creating a data model by applying formal data model descriptions using data modeling techniques.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data modeling is a technique for defining business requirements for a database.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It is sometimes called *database modeling* because a data model is eventually implemented in a database.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The figure illustrates the way data models are developed and used today.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A conceptual data model is developed based on the data requirements for the application that is being developed, perhaps in the context of an activity model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The data model will normally consist of entity types, attributes, relationships, integrity rules, and the definitions of those objects.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This is then used as the start point for interface or database design.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Another kind of data model describes how to organize data using a database management system or other data management technology.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It describes, for example, relational tables and columns or object-oriented classes and attributes.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Such a data model is sometimes referred to as the *physical data model*, but in the original ANSI three schema architecture, it is called "logical".
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In that architecture, the physical model describes the storage media (cylinders, tracks, and tablespaces).
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Ideally, this model is derived from the more conceptual data model described above.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It may differ, however, to account for constraints like processing capacity and usage patterns.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A different approach is to use adaptive systems such as artificial neural networks that can autonomously create implicit models of data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data structure is a way of storing data in a computer so that it can be used efficiently.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It is an organization of mathematical and logical concepts of data.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Often a carefully chosen data structure will allow the most efficient algorithm to be used.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The choice of the data structure often begins from the choice of an abstract data type.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data model describes the structure of the data within a given domain and, by implication, the underlying structure of that domain itself.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This means that a data model in fact specifies a dedicated *grammar* for a dedicated artificial language for that domain.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data model represents classes of entities (kinds of things) about which a company wishes to hold information, the attributes of that information, and relationships among those entities and (often implicit) relationships among those attributes.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The model describes the organization of the data to some extent irrespective of how data might be represented in a computer system.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The entities represented by a data model can be the tangible entities, but models that include such concrete entity classes tend to change over time.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Robust data models often identify abstractions of such entities.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] For example, a data model might include an entity class called "Person", representing all the people who interact with an organization.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Such an abstract entity class is typically more appropriate than ones called "Vendor" or "Employee", which identify specific roles played by those people.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data model *instance*, i.e. applying a data model *theory* to create a practical data model *instance* for some particular application.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] For example, in the relational model, the structural part is based on a modified concept of the mathematical relation; the integrity part is expressed in first-order logic and the manipulation part is expressed using the relational algebra, tuple calculus and domain calculus.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data model instance is created by applying a data model theory.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This is typically done to solve some business enterprise requirement.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Business requirements are normally captured by a semantic logical data model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This is transformed into a physical data model instance from which is generated a physical database.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] For example, a data modeler may use a data modeling tool to create an entity–relationship model of the corporate data repository of some business enterprise.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] This model is transformed into a relational model, which in turn generates a relational database.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Patterns are common data modeling structures that occur in many data models.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data-flow diagram (DFD) is a graphical representation of the "flow" of data through an information system.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It differs from the flowchart as it shows the *data* flow instead of the *control* flow of the program.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] A data-flow diagram can also be used for the visualization of data processing (structured design).
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Data-flow diagrams were invented by Larry Constantine, the original developer of structured design, based on Martin and Estrin's "data-flow graph" model of computation.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It is common practice to draw a context-level data-flow diagram first which shows the interaction between the system and outside entities.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The **DFD** is designed to show how a system is divided into smaller portions and to highlight the flow of data between those parts.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] An Information model is not a type of data model, but more or less an alternative model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Within the field of software engineering, both a data model and an information model can be abstract, formal representations of entity types that include their properties, relationships and the operations that can be performed on them.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The entity types in the model may be kinds of real-world objects, such as devices in a network, or they may themselves be abstract, such as for the entities used in a billing system.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Typically, they are used to model a constrained domain that can be described by a closed set of entity types, properties, relationships and operations.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] According to Lee (1999) an information model is a representation of concepts, relationships, constraints, rules, and operations to specify data semantics for a chosen domain of discourse.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It can provide sharable, stable, and organized structure of information requirements for the domain context.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] More in general the term *information model* is used for models of individual things, such as facilities, buildings, process plants, etc.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In those cases the concept is specialised to Facility Information Model, Building Information Model, Plant Information Model, etc.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Such an information model is an integration of a model of the facility with the data and documents about the facility.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] An information model provides formalism to the description of a problem domain without constraining how that description is mapped to an actual implementation in software.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] There may be many mappings of the information model.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Such mappings are called data models, irrespective of whether they are object models (e.g. using UML), entity–relationship models or XML schemas.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] An object model in computer science is a collection of objects or classes through which a program can examine and manipulate some specific parts of its world.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In other words, the object-oriented interface to some service or system.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Such an interface is said to be the *object model of* the represented service or system.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] For example, the Document Object Model (DOM) [1] is a collection of objects that represent a page in a web browser, used by script programs to examine and dynamically change the page.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] There is a Microsoft Excel object model for controlling Microsoft Excel from another program, and the ASCOM Telescope Driver is an object model for controlling an astronomical telescope.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] In computing the term *object model* has a distinct second meaning of the general properties of objects in a specific computer programming language, technology, notation or methodology that uses them.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] For example, the *Java object model*, the *COM object model*, or *the object model of OMT*.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Such object models are usually defined using concepts such as class, message, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] There is an extensive literature on formalized object models as a subset of the formal semantics of programming languages.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Object–Role Modeling (ORM) is a method for conceptual modeling, and can be used as a tool for information and rules analysis.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] Object–Role Modeling is a fact-oriented method for performing systems analysis at the conceptual level.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The quality of a database application depends critically on its design.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] To help ensure correctness, clarity, adaptability and productivity, information systems are best specified first at the conceptual level, using concepts and language that people can readily understand.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The conceptual design may include data, process and behavioral perspectives, and the actual DBMS used to implement the design might be based on one of many logical data models (relational, hierarchic, network, object-oriented, etc.).
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] The Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a standardized general-purpose modeling language in the field of software engineering.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] It is a graphical language for visualizing, specifying, constructing, and documenting the artifacts of a software-intensive system.
[src:structured-data-schema/structured-data] UML offers a mix of functional models, data models, and database models.
